An automatically generated table of contents (ToC) is a useful feature in long documents. In LATEX, you can create a ToC using the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example of a LATEX document with an automatically generated table of contents:
```latex
\documentclass[12pt,a4paper]{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{booktabs}
\usepackage{tocbasic}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is an example of an automatically generated table of contents in a LATEX document. The ToC is created using the \verb|\tableofcontents| command, which is placed inside the document where the table of contents should appear.

\section{Table of Contents}
\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{@{}ll@{}}
\toprule
Section & Page \\
\midrule
\section{Introduction} & 1 \\
\section{Table of Contents} & 2 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\section{Conclusion}
This document demonstrates how a table of contents can be generated automatically in a LATEX document using the \verb|\tableofcontents| command. The table of contents is updated automatically as new sections are added, making it easy to maintain.

\end{document}
```
In this example, we use the `tocbasic` package to create a simple table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command. You can customize the appearance of the ToC by using other LATEX packages or modifying the ToC template. To view the ToC, compile the document with a LATEX compiler, and the ToC will be generated automatically.

Here are a few LaTeX templates for homework assignments that you can use as a starting point for your project:

1. `homework.tex`: This is a basic LaTeX template for a homework assignment, which can be easily customized.
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{geometry}
\geometry{margin=1in}

\title{Homework Assignment}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\section{Introduction}

\section{Task}

\section{Solution}

\section{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```
2. `homework\_template.tex`: This is a more advanced LaTeX template that includes a title page and table of contents.
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{geometry}
\geometry{margin=1in}
\usepackage{titletoc}

\title{Homework Assignment}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}

\section{Task}

\section{Solution}

\section{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```
3. `homework.cls`: This is a custom LaTeX class for creating homework assignments, which allows you to use a shorter file name and a standard structure for your documents.
```latex
\NeedsTeXFormat{LaTeX2e}
\ProvidesClass{homework}
\LoadClass{article}
\RequirePackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\RequirePackage{geometry}
\geometry{margin=1in}
\RequirePackage{titletoc}

\titleformat{\section}
{\normalfont\Large\bfseries}
{\thesection}
{1em}
{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}

\section{Task}

\section{Solution}

\section{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```

You can use any of these templates as a starting point for your project and modify them as needed. To use them, save the respective `.tex` file or `.cls` file with the appropriate name, and then compile the document using a LaTeX compiler (such as `pdflatex`, `xelatex`, or `lualatex`, depending on your system and requirements).

Sure! Here's a Java solution to the problem using bit manipulation without loops or recursion:
```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // Output: true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // Output: false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // Output: false
    }

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n == 0) return false;

        int mask = 1 << 30;
        int shift = 30;

        while (mask > 0) {
            if ((n & mask) != 0) {
                int x = 30 - Integer.numberOfLeadingZeros(n);
                if (x > 0) {
                    return (n >>> (shift - x)) == 3;
                }
            }
            mask >>= 1;
            shift--;
        }

        return false;
    }
}
```
This code uses bit manipulation to check if the input integer is a power of three. It sets the most significant bit (MSB) of the integer to 1 and then iteratively sets the lower bits to 0. If the number of leading zeros in the integer is equal to the shift value, it means that the number is a power of three.

For example, if we have n = 27, we set the MSB to 1 and shift the bits to the right, so we have:

27 (binary) = 11001 (after shifting)

The number of leading zeros in 11001 is 2, which means that 27 = 3^2. Thus, the function returns true.

Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int count_word(const std::string &word, const std::string &file_path) {
    std::ifstream file(file_path);
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file: " << file_path << std::endl;
        return 0;
    }

    int count = 0;
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        if (line.find(word) != std::string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string word = "example";
    std::string file_path = "example.txt";
    int count = count_word(word, file_path);

    std::cout << "The word '" << word << "' appears " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```
This program defines a `count_word` function that takes a word and a file path as arguments. It opens the file using the `std::ifstream` class and reads it line by line using the `std::getline` function. It then counts the number of occurrences of the word in the file by checking if each line contains the word using the `std::string::find` function. The function returns the count of occurrences.

In the `main` function, the program reads the word and file path from the user and calls the `count_word` function with the user-provided values. It then displays the count of occurrences to the user. Note that this program assumes that the word is a subsequence of the lines in the file, and does not consider word boundaries (e.g., spaces, punctuation) in the text.

