Here's a method called `isPalindrome` that takes a `String` parameter and returns a `boolean` value indicating whether the parameter is a palindrome or not:
```java
public static boolean isPalindrome(String input) {
    if (input == null || input.isEmpty()) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Input string cannot be null or empty.");
    }

    String cleanedString = input.toLowerCase().replaceAll("\\s+|[^a-zA-Z]+", "").trim();

    if (cleanedString.length() == 0) {
        return true;
    }

    String[] words = cleanedString.split("[^a-zA-Z]+");

    for (int i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
        if (!isSingleCharacterPalindrome(words[i])) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}

private static boolean isSingleCharacterPalindrome(String character) {
    return character.length() == 1 && Character.isAlphabetic(character.charAt(0)) && character.equals(Character.toUpperCase(character.charAt(0))) && character.equals(Character.toLowerCase(character.charAt(0)));
}
```
The `isPalindrome` method first checks if the input string is null or empty. If so, it throws an IllegalArgumentException. Then, it converts the input string to lowercase, removes spaces and non-letter characters, and trims the resulting string. If the trimmed string is empty, it returns true, as an empty string is considered a palindrome.

Next, the method splits the cleaned string into an array of words based on non-letter characters. It then iterates through the words and checks if each word is a single-character palindrome using the `isSingleCharacterPalindrome` method. If a word is not a palindrome, the method returns false. If all words are palindromes, the method returns true.

The `isSingleCharacterPalindrome` method checks if a single-character string is a palindrome by verifying that it has a length of 1, contains an alphabetic character, and is equal to its uppercase and lowercase versions.

Below, we compare and contrast seven common sorting algorithms - Bubble Sort, Insertion Sort, Selection Sort, Merge Sort, Quick Sort, and Heap Sort. We will analyze their time and space complexities using Big-O notation and provide a simple C++ code example for each.

1. Bubble Sort:
Time Complexity: O(n^2)
Space Complexity: O(n)
Bubble Sort works by repeatedly stepping through the list, comparing each pair of adjacent elements and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. The algorithm continues to iterate through the list until no more swaps are needed.

C++ Example:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

void bubbleSort(vector<int>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size();

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - 1 - i; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                arr[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {6, 4, 2, 1};
    bubbleSort(arr);

    for (int item : arr) {
        cout << item << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}
```
1. Insertion Sort:
Time Complexity: O(n^2)
Space Complexity: O(n)
Insertion Sort works by dividing the input list into a sorted list and a "sorted" list. It iteratively selects an element from the unsorted list and inserts it into its correct position in the sorted list.

C++ Example:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

void insertionSort(vector<int>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size();
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        int key = arr[i];
        int j = i - 1;
        while (j >= 0 && key < arr[j]) {
            arr[j + 1] = arr[j];
            j--;
        }
        arr[j + 1] = key;
    }
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {6, 4, 2, 1};
    insertionSort(arr);

    for (int item : arr) {
        cout << item << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}
```
1. Selection Sort:
Time Complexity: O(n^2)
Space Complexity: O(n)
Selection Sort works by repeatedly selecting the smallest (or largest) element from the unsorted list and placing it at the front (or end) of the sorted list. This process is repeated until the entire list is sorted.

C++ Example:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

void selectionSort(vector<int>& arr, bool sortInDecreasingOrder) {
    int n = arr.size();
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int minIndex = i;
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if (sortInDecreasingOrder ? arr[j] < arr[minIndex] : arr[j] > arr[minIndex]) {
                minIndex = j;
            }
        }
        if (!sortInDecreasingOrder) {
            swap(arr[i], arr[minIndex]);
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {6, 4, 2, 1};
    selectionSort(arr, false);

    for (int item : arr) {
        cout << item << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}
```

It looks like you are trying to implement the quicksort algorithm. However, there are a few issues with your code. First, you are using the 'swap' function, which is a built-in function, and second, you are not choosing the pivot correctly.

To avoid using the 'swap' function, you can use two pointers to swap elements. For the pivot selection, you can choose the last element in the array as the pivot, since it is the most common case in the quicksort algorithm.

Here is the corrected version of your code:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void quicksort(int nums[], int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pivotIndex = partition(nums, low, high);
        quicksort(nums, low, pivotIndex - 1);
        quicksort(nums, pivotIndex + 1, high);
    }
}

int partition(int nums[], int low, int high) {
    int pivot = nums[high];
    int i = low - 1;
    int j = low;

    for (int k = low; k <= high; k++) {
        if (nums[k] <= pivot) {
            j++;
            swap(nums[i], nums[j]);
        }
    }
    swap(nums[i], nums[j]);
    return j;
}

int main() {
    int nums[] = {5, 2, 9, 1, 5, 6};
    int n = sizeof(nums) / sizeof(nums[0]);

    quicksort(nums, 0, n - 1);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << nums[i] << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This implementation of the quicksort algorithm has a time complexity of O(nlog(n)) and uses only pass-by-reference for the function calls, which has a smaller space complexity.

