To sort the array in ascending order with the given constraints, you can use the following solution:

1. Find the minimum element in the array and swap it with the first element.
2. Repeat the previous step until the minimum element is in its correct position (at index 0).

Here's the Java implementation of the solution:
```java
public class ArraySort {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {5, 2, 3, 1};
        int[] result = sortArray(nums);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(result)); // [1, 2, 3, 5]
    }

    public static int[] sortArray(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int minPos = 0;

        while (minPos < n) {
            minPos = findMin(nums, minPos, n);
            swap(nums, 0, minPos);
            n--;
        }

        return nums;
    }

    public static int findMin(int[] array, int start, int end) {
        while (start < end) {
            int temp = array[start];
            array[start] = array[end];
            array[end] = temp;

            start++;
            end--;
        }

        return array[start];
    }

    public static void swap(int[] array, int i, int j) {
        int temp = array[i];
        array[i] = array[j];
        array[j] = temp;
    }
}
```
This implementation has a time complexity of O(nlog(n)) and space complexity of O(1), as required.

